In this article, President Barack Obama proclaims April 28, 2013, as Workers Memorial Day. He acknowledges the importance of American workers and their contributions to the economy. However, he also highlights the tragic reality that thousands of workers die on the job each year, with millions more suffering from work-related injuries or illnesses. The President emphasizes the need to protect workers and ensure their safety. He mentions the historical struggles of laborers and the progress made through union organizers and advocates. The Federal Coal Mine Health and Safety Act of 1969 and the Occupational Safety and Health Act of 1970 are highlighted as important legislation that established safety standards for workers. The President expresses condolences for those who have lost loved ones to workplace accidents or illnesses and calls for action and accountability. He concludes by urging all Americans to participate in ceremonies and activities in memory of those affected by unsafe working conditions.